Diagnostic probes for run_fp4_blockwise_scaled_group_mm_sm120.

Problem:
  `gemm_op.run()` in nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh is an async kernel launch.
  Any runtime failure (device-side assert, invalid dynamic SMEM,
  illegal instruction, out-of-bounds) does not surface at the launch
  site — it propagates as a sticky stream error and is reported at
  the NEXT sync-point, which is typically `cudaMallocAsync` inside
  `get_cached_workspace()` during the SUBSEQUENT call. That sync-point
  happens to be at nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh:78, so every crash along
  the sm120 path shows up as "Runtime check failed at line 78"
  regardless of what actually broke.

  Worse: the failing kernel might not even be our cutlass GEMM. The
  triton MoE runner calls several upstream kernels (topk, expert
  gather, scale factor reshuffle) BEFORE calling cutlass_fp4_group_mm.
  Any of those upstream kernels can set the stream error state, and
  then OUR function's first CUDA op (the workspace alloc) reports
  the error as if it originated here.

Fix:
  Insert TWO diagnostic probes in run_fp4_blockwise_scaled_group_mm_sm120():

    1. Pre-workspace probe (ENTRY side). Right after `const
       cudaStream_t stream = ...` and BEFORE `get_cached_workspace`,
       call cudaStreamSynchronize + cudaGetLastError and print a
       diagnostic line if the stream is already in error state. This
       distinguishes "upstream kernel asserted" from "our kernel
       asserted" — if this probe reports an error, the assertion is
       from a kernel launched BEFORE this function was entered
       (topk, expert gather, scale reshuffle, etc.). If this probe
       reports clean, the assertion must be from OUR gemm_op.run().

    2. Post-launch probe (EXIT side). Immediately after `gemm_op.run`
       returns, call cudaStreamSynchronize + cudaGetLastError again
       and print the result. This catches assertions from our main
       GEMM kernel at their actual launch site (without waiting for
       the next sync-point to surface them).

  Both probes are gated at runtime by the `DGXARLEY_SM121_DEBUG` env
  var. When unset, the `static const bool` is false on first touch
  and the branch is folded away — near-zero production overhead. When
  set to any value, both probes fire on every sm120 GEMM invocation.
  No rebuild required to toggle — set the env var in the sglang pod.

  Gated at BUILD time by `APPLY_SGL_KERNEL_SM121_DEBUG` build-arg
  (default 0, opt-in via `--sm121-debug` in build_sm121_image.sh).
  When 0, this patch is skipped entirely and the upstream .cuh is
  used as-is, so production builds have zero footprint from this.

  Only touches the sm120 path (run_fp4_blockwise_scaled_group_mm_sm120).
  The sm100 sibling path at ~line 636 is left untouched because GB10
  never dispatches to it.

Diagnostic output format:

  "[dgxarley sm121-debug] sm120 pre-workspace clean (num_experts=N)"
      → entry probe sees no prior error, our function is the first
        to touch a clean stream since the last sync

  "[dgxarley sm121-debug] sm120 PRE-WORKSPACE stream error: ...
       -- UPSTREAM kernel asserted, not our cutlass GEMM"
      → entry probe sees a pre-existing error, some kernel launched
        BEFORE this function was called is the asserting one. Not
        a CUTLASS issue — look at the triton MoE preprocessing chain.

  "[dgxarley sm121-debug] sm120 post-launch OK (num_experts=N)"
      → our gemm_op.run() succeeded

  "[dgxarley sm121-debug] sm120 post-launch error: ...
       -- OUR cutlass GEMM kernel asserted"
      → our kernel is the failing one; the CUTLASS CollectiveBuilder
        / schedule / stage count / tile shape combination has a
        runtime invariant that GB10 violates

Stacking:
  This patch is designed to stack on top of sgl-kernel-sm121.patch
  (the StageCount<2> + Cooperative-schedule fix). `patch` auto-offsets
  the hunk line numbers when applied in sequence. Safe to apply on
  pristine upstream too (standalone), but the intended workflow is
  sm121 patch first, then debug.

Apply to: python/sglang/jit_kernel/csrc/moe/nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh,
inside the Dockerfile builder stage, LATE (same layer as the main
sgl-kernel-sm121.patch — this is a JIT kernel header not touched by
the sgl-kernel C++ wheel build).

Upstream source: sgl-project/sglang tag v0.5.10

--- a/python/sglang/jit_kernel/csrc/moe/nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh
+++ b/python/sglang/jit_kernel/csrc/moe/nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh
@@ -431,6 +431,34 @@
 
   size_t workspace_size = Gemm::get_workspace_size(args);
   const cudaStream_t stream = LaunchKernel::resolve_device(a.device());
+
+  // dgxarley sgl-kernel-sm121-debug.patch: pre-workspace stream error probe.
+  // The device-side-assert observed at cuh:78 (cudaMallocAsync) is the next
+  // sync-point after an assert. We probe BEFORE calling cudaMallocAsync so
+  // we can distinguish "this function's kernel asserted" from "upstream
+  // kernel asserted, we are just the sync point". Gated by DGXARLEY_SM121_DEBUG
+  // env var. sm120 path only — the sm100 sibling below is unmodified.
+  {
+    static const bool _dgx_entry = (std::getenv("DGXARLEY_SM121_DEBUG") != nullptr);
+    if (_dgx_entry) {
+      cudaError_t _sync = cudaStreamSynchronize(stream);
+      cudaError_t _last = cudaGetLastError();
+      if (_sync != cudaSuccess || _last != cudaSuccess) {
+        std::fprintf(stderr,
+          "[dgxarley sm121-debug] sm120 PRE-WORKSPACE stream error: "
+          "sync=%d (%s) last=%d (%s) -- UPSTREAM kernel asserted, "
+          "not our cutlass GEMM\n",
+          (int)_sync, cudaGetErrorString(_sync),
+          (int)_last, cudaGetErrorString(_last));
+        std::fflush(stderr);
+      } else {
+        std::fprintf(stderr,
+          "[dgxarley sm121-debug] sm120 pre-workspace clean (num_experts=%d)\n",
+          num_experts);
+        std::fflush(stderr);
+      }
+    }
+  }
   void* workspace = get_cached_workspace(workspace_size, hw_info.device_id, stream);
 
   auto can_implement_status = gemm_op.can_implement(args);
@@ -445,6 +473,30 @@
 
   status = gemm_op.run(args, workspace, stream);
   RuntimeCheck(status == cutlass::Status::kSuccess, "Failed to run GEMM: ", cutlassGetStatusString(status));
+
+  // dgxarley sgl-kernel-sm121-debug.patch: post-launch error probe.
+  {
+    static const bool _dgx_post = (std::getenv("DGXARLEY_SM121_DEBUG") != nullptr);
+    if (_dgx_post) {
+      cudaError_t _sync_err = cudaStreamSynchronize(stream);
+      cudaError_t _last_err = cudaGetLastError();
+      if (_sync_err != cudaSuccess || _last_err != cudaSuccess) {
+        std::fprintf(stderr,
+          "[dgxarley sm121-debug] sm120 post-launch error: "
+          "sync=%d (%s) last=%d (%s) num_experts=%d -- OUR cutlass "
+          "GEMM kernel asserted\n",
+          (int)_sync_err, cudaGetErrorString(_sync_err),
+          (int)_last_err, cudaGetErrorString(_last_err),
+          num_experts);
+        std::fflush(stderr);
+      } else {
+        std::fprintf(stderr,
+          "[dgxarley sm121-debug] sm120 post-launch OK (num_experts=%d)\n",
+          num_experts);
+        std::fflush(stderr);
+      }
+    }
+  }
 }
 
